<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Confessed hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi said he was one of two hooded 
hostage-takers who appeared at a Beirut news conference during the 1985 
hijacking of a TWA jetliner. Hamadi, charged with air piracy and murder in the 
hijacking, made the admission in court in Frankfurt, West Germany, after 
officials watched a videotape of the news conference. A U.S. Navy diver was 
killed and 39 Americans were held hostage for 17 days after the plane was 
diverted to Beirut. Hamadi has previously admitted his part in the hijacking 
but denies the murder charge. 
</P>
