<P>
SOUTH AFRICA FREES 50 DETAINEES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, South Africa 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The government freed 50 more detainees today after hunger strikes were halted 
at two prisons, but scores of detainees continued to fast elsewhere and police 
said 20 were hospitalized. 
</P>
<P>
Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok told Parliament he had signed release 
warrants for 50 detainees. About 225 detainees still are refusing food at 
prisons in the southern cities of Durban, Pietermaritzburg and East London, 
their lawyers said. The first wave of hunger strikes began Jan. 23 and involved 
nearly 300 detainees who broke their fast after Vlok promised to review their 
cases and release "a substantial number." 
</P>
</TEXT>
