<P>
EPA WANTS TO FINE 109 REPAIR SHOPS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Environmental Protection Agency proposed fines of more than $1 million 
against 109 muffler and car repair shops today for installing improper 
emission-control devices on automobiles. 
</P>
<P>
The EPA said the shops installed cheaper, less effective "two-way" catalytic 
converters on automobiles rather than the "three-way" converters required under 
federal laws to reduce air pollution. 
</P>
<P>
The three-way converters control nitrogen oxide emissions in addition to 
hydrocarbons and carbon monoxide in car exhaust. The two-way converters do not 
adequately control nitrogen oxides, the EPA said. 
</P>
